And speaking of little Tom,

00:54.867 --> 00:57.367
all our acts tonight face
a real-life <i>Mission: Impossible.</i>

00:57.433 --> 01:00.833
They have to try to fool
two of the greatest magicians of our time.

01:01.067 --> 01:03.733
Now, should they manage
to achieve that incredible feat,

01:03.800 --> 01:05.867
they will earn a starring guest spot

01:05.933 --> 01:08.600
in Penn and Teller's
long-running Vegas spectacular.

01:11.667 --> 01:13.867
Now let's meet the men
whose legend is even bigger

01:13.933 --> 01:15.267
than their billboards around Vegas.

01:15.333 --> 01:18.367
And they're huge, they're enormous,
much bigger than Criss Angel's.

01:18.433 --> 01:19.433
His are tiny.

01:19.567 --> 01:21.667
Please go crazy for Penn and Teller.

01:22.400 --> 01:24.400
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

01:24.467 --> 01:26.733
(UPBEAT INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

01:27.800 --> 01:30.967
Mr. Teller, great to see you.
Great to have you here.

01:31.033 --> 01:33.833
Here they are, Penn and Teller,
ladies and gentlemen.

01:33.900 --> 01:35.567
(CHEERING)

01:36.567 --> 01:38.400
Backstage, I've spoken
to some of the guys.

01:38.467 --> 01:40.067
Some of them are very, very nervous.

01:40.133 --> 01:42.300
Some are sweating.
Some have their heart racing.

01:42.367 --> 01:45.000
One or two said
they've lost the ability to speak.

01:45.067 --> 01:46.933
-Have you ever been nervous in that way?
-(MOUTHING)

01:47.000 --> 01:48.100
#@*! no.

01:48.200 --> 01:49.900
(LAUGHING)

01:49.967 --> 01:51.433
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

01:56.400 --> 01:58.167
Ladies and gentlemen,
it's Penn and Teller.

01:58.233 --> 02:00.700
You get yourselves comfortable, gentlemen.

02:00.767 --> 02:02.633
-(LAUGHING)
-(APPLAUSE)

02:06.267 --> 02:07.900
Penn and Teller.

02:09.199 --> 02:11.700
Let's meet our first potential fooler.

02:14.900 --> 02:16.800
<i>I'm Leon Etienne from Utica, New York.</i>

02:16.867 --> 02:18.933
And I'm Romy Low
from Melbourne, Australia.

02:19.000 --> 02:22.133
And we are Leon and Romy,
America's rock illusionists.

02:22.500 --> 02:24.400
I think what makes our magic unique

02:24.467 --> 02:28.100
is we bring both of our very strong
personalities to everything we do.

02:28.167 --> 02:31.200
<i>We have a lot of fast-paced illusions,</i>
<i>a lot of fast-paced magic,</i>

02:31.267 --> 02:33.100
so it's basically a magic show...

02:33.167 --> 02:34.467
ROMY: <i>With a rock concert.</i>

02:34.533 --> 02:38.533
When I first met Leon,
I thought he was incredibly cocky,

02:38.600 --> 02:41.433
<i>and his confidence, I think,</i>
<i>rubbed off on me,</i>

02:41.500 --> 02:45.133
and then we ended up
to just really get along really well

02:45.200 --> 02:49.100
and fell in love with a magician,
and then my life changed forever.

02:49.167 --> 02:51.367
I think Penn and Teller
are absolutely incredible.

02:51.433 --> 02:54.067
-But we're a cuter couple.
-Yeah, we're cuter.

02:54.467 --> 02:55.500
(GIGGLES)

02:55.567 --> 02:56.733
(APPLAUSE)

02:56.800 --> 02:59.600
Will you please welcome Leon and Romy?

02:59.867 --> 03:01.467
(APPLAUSE)

03:05.533 --> 03:07.500
-My name's Leon.
-And I'm Romy.

03:07.567 --> 03:10.400
And it is an honor to be here
at <i>Penn &amp; Teller: Fool Us.</i>

03:10.467 --> 03:11.500
It really is.

03:11.567 --> 03:14.500
Both Leon and I are each holding
a clear plastic bag,

03:14.567 --> 03:17.400
each containing
10 different decks of cards.

03:17.600 --> 03:19.633
That's 20 different decks of cards.

03:19.700 --> 03:24.467
Which gives us 1,040 cards
for Mr. Jonathan Ross to choose from.

03:24.533 --> 03:26.100
Jonathan, please join me
over here onstage.

03:26.167 --> 03:28.733
-Let's hear it for Jonathan!
-(APPLAUSE)

03:28.800 --> 03:31.100
-Thank you, sir.
-My pleasure, my pleasure. It's exciting.

03:31.167 --> 03:32.400
Very exciting.

03:32.767 --> 03:35.100
Teller, point to a bag of cards.

03:36.267 --> 03:39.833
Mine? Ah, I'm so excited.
I was really hoping you would pick me.

03:39.900 --> 03:43.133
That means that everything
that Leon is holding is useless.

03:43.200 --> 03:44.367
Done.

03:44.433 --> 03:47.867
Jonathan, please select one deck of cards.

03:48.000 --> 03:51.567
The choice is 100% yours,
but whichever deck you choose...

03:51.633 --> 03:53.200
LEON: Is the one we will use.
ROMY: Ah!

03:53.267 --> 03:55.533
And you got this
nifty-looking deck of cards.

03:55.600 --> 03:57.133
Can you hold on to the box for me?

03:57.200 --> 03:59.333
We're going to start
by shuffling the cards,

03:59.400 --> 04:03.567
so we know we're starting with
a well-mixed pack of playing cards.

04:03.633 --> 04:06.467
And, Jonathan, if you wouldn't mind,
please reach in there and touch a card.

04:06.567 --> 04:08.600
-Okay.
-Any one. Doesn't matter.

04:08.667 --> 04:09.800
-That one? Take it, take it.
-Okay.

04:09.867 --> 04:11.600
And it's okay if I see it.
You can show it to me.

04:11.667 --> 04:12.733
I'm not showing it to you.

04:12.800 --> 04:13.967
-You got to show it to me.
-Show it to us.

04:14.033 --> 04:15.100
Where's the fun in that? Where's the...

04:15.167 --> 04:17.533
-Show it to them, at least.
-Let's see, what...

04:17.600 --> 04:21.267
The 10 of Diamonds. So, folks,
Jonathan got the 10 of Diamonds.

04:21.333 --> 04:23.700
And to make this official,
we're gonna have you put your name on it.

04:23.767 --> 04:26.633
So take this marker and sign your name
on the face of that card.

04:26.700 --> 04:28.500
This is the only one
you've ever signed for us, correct, sir?

04:28.567 --> 04:29.700
-It certainly is.
-Correct.

04:29.767 --> 04:32.167
-And I will take that back.
-So there we go, guys.

04:32.233 --> 04:34.767
Ten of Diamonds
with Jonathan's signature.

04:34.833 --> 04:35.933
We're now going to take that card

04:36.000 --> 04:37.733
and, Jonathan,
can you confirm for everybody out there

04:37.800 --> 04:39.967
that I am shuffling
this pack of playing cards

04:40.033 --> 04:44.133
and that we are mixing your card
amongst all these other cards?

04:44.200 --> 04:46.233
ROSS: Fully shuffled.
LEON: Perfect.

04:46.300 --> 04:49.000
Now, ladies and gentlemen,
Penn and Teller, Jonathan,

04:49.067 --> 04:52.433
the idea here is to now try
and find Jonathan's card.

04:52.500 --> 04:54.633
But I want to do this in a unique way

04:54.700 --> 04:57.533
and a really dangerous way,
actually, as well.

04:57.600 --> 04:58.767
In fact, this is so dangerous

04:58.833 --> 05:02.100
that the producers were worried
about Jonathan's safety,

05:02.167 --> 05:07.067
so they actually asked me
to provide him with a safety helmet.

05:07.133 --> 05:11.400
But, Jonathan, this is Las Vegas,
so we have something a little different.

05:11.733 --> 05:13.133
(LAUGHTER)

05:13.667 --> 05:15.267
-(APPLAUSE)
-Go ahead, man.

05:15.333 --> 05:16.767
For me? Okay.

05:19.867 --> 05:22.933
-LEON: Do you feel safe, sir?
-I'm channeling my inner showgirl.

05:23.000 --> 05:24.867
LEON: (LAUGHING) You look wonderful.

05:24.933 --> 05:26.800
(ALL LAUGHING)

05:27.367 --> 05:30.900
-(APPLAUSE)
-Take a seat. Go, go.

05:31.467 --> 05:33.267
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

05:33.900 --> 05:35.000
LEON: Romy?
ROMY: All right.

05:35.067 --> 05:36.500
As Leon said earlier,

05:36.567 --> 05:40.433
the trick that we are about to perform
is actually incredibly dangerous,

05:40.500 --> 05:42.600
and we do need a few more items.

05:42.667 --> 05:45.833
The first one's been sitting center stage
the entire show.

05:45.900 --> 05:47.500
It's this ramp.

05:47.567 --> 05:49.633
Now, guys, this ramp
is not going to make sense to you

05:49.700 --> 05:51.433
until I introduce this next person.

05:51.500 --> 05:53.600
This is our friend Jason from Las Vegas.

05:53.667 --> 05:55.400
-(APPLAUSE)
-He is a professional skateboarder.

05:55.467 --> 05:58.367
Jason, thank you for joining us.
Are you ready to help us out today?

06:00.700 --> 06:02.633
Ladies and gentlemen,
we take the packet of cards,

06:02.700 --> 06:05.933
we split it into two,
so Romy has a packet, I have a packet.

06:06.000 --> 06:09.267
Um, Jonathan,
your card's in one of these packets.

06:09.333 --> 06:14.167
Here's where it gets very interesting.
Romy and I are going to sit on the stage.

06:14.233 --> 06:15.767
Ladies and gentlemen,
I'm going to need your help.

06:15.833 --> 06:17.400
I'm going to say, "Go." When I say, "Go,"

06:17.467 --> 06:20.733
I would ask that you all together count,
"Three, two, one."

06:20.800 --> 06:24.000
Now when you get to one,
Jason is going to come flying over us,

06:24.067 --> 06:26.300
in mid-air,
we're going to spring these cards.

06:26.367 --> 06:30.367
He's going to reach in mid-air
like a skateboarding flying ninja...

06:30.433 --> 06:31.867
-Hiyah!
-Hiyah!

06:31.933 --> 06:35.033
...and catch Jonathan's signed card
in mid-air.

06:35.133 --> 06:36.667
Pretty good. Are you guys ready?

06:37.000 --> 06:38.200
-ALL: Yeah!
-Jason.

06:38.267 --> 06:41.500
Are you ready, Jason?
All right. Ready? Go.

06:41.567 --> 06:43.967
ALL: Three, two, one!

06:44.367 --> 06:45.733
Come on, baby.

06:46.600 --> 06:48.800
-(APPLAUSE)
-Yes!

06:49.500 --> 06:53.833
Jason, come over here
and bring us the signed card, please.

06:53.900 --> 06:57.667
-Oh, I didn't get it. Didn't catch it.
-You... You're serious?

06:57.733 --> 06:59.633
-Yeah, I didn't get it.
-Really?

06:59.733 --> 07:01.633
Well, it was
a heck of a jump anyway, right?

07:01.700 --> 07:02.933
Yeah.

07:03.833 --> 07:05.300
Thanks, man. Thanks.

07:05.367 --> 07:07.200
Uh, Jonathan,
can you please come over here

07:07.267 --> 07:09.500
and help us find your card on the floor?

07:10.400 --> 07:13.467
Guys, I'll be honest with you.
It would have been too easy

07:13.533 --> 07:17.067
to have Jason fly in mid-air
and catch that playing card.

07:17.467 --> 07:22.600
The hard part of this trick
was actually getting the signed card

07:23.033 --> 07:24.700
on the bottom of the skateboard.

07:24.767 --> 07:26.133
-Jonathan, is that your card?
-ROSS: That is my card.

07:26.200 --> 07:27.367
ROMY: And your signature.

07:27.433 --> 07:28.833
-And your handwriting?
-That is my card.

07:28.900 --> 07:31.333
-It is. Thank you, I'm Leon.
-And I'm Romy.

07:31.400 --> 07:32.800
LEON: Thank you.

07:34.967 --> 07:36.400
Penn and Teller are going to
talk about what they saw

07:36.467 --> 07:39.333
and see whether or not they know
how you did what you just did.

07:39.400 --> 07:40.900
Is it something
they would have seen before,

07:40.967 --> 07:43.133
maybe in a different form,
or is this a brand-new illusion?

07:43.200 --> 07:45.133
Probably, maybe in a different form.

07:45.200 --> 07:47.833
I mean, there's a lot of tricks
that are like this

07:47.900 --> 07:52.067
where it's basically a signed card
going to an impossible location.

07:52.133 --> 07:53.167
We'll see how we did.

07:53.233 --> 07:55.233
Well, it worked, certainly,
in fooling us, I think.

07:55.300 --> 07:57.000
Whether or not you fooled
the two maestros, I don't know.

07:57.067 --> 07:59.100
I might take this hat off
because I'm, A...

07:59.167 --> 08:00.300
-Hurt your neck?
-...getting a headache,

08:00.367 --> 08:02.900
and, B, I'm thinking about
having an operation, so...

08:02.967 --> 08:05.367
-(ALL LAUGHING)
-Penn, take it away.

08:05.433 --> 08:09.900
You know, what we do in magic,
the major job to do in magic

08:10.000 --> 08:14.267
is to take card tricks and try desperately
to make them interesting.

08:14.967 --> 08:18.300
That is what...
That is the grail we're all looking for,

08:18.367 --> 08:21.033
and I think you've got your finger
on that grail very, very well.

08:21.267 --> 08:25.967
The one thing that led us
to be able to, we think, figure this out,

08:26.667 --> 08:30.167
is, uh, how interesting it is

08:30.633 --> 08:33.667
to watch you walk across the stage.

08:34.200 --> 08:36.533
-You walk so nicely...
-Thank you.

08:36.600 --> 08:40.433
...across the stage
that we could not take our eyes off you.

08:40.500 --> 08:41.667
Hey, Penn, one minute.

08:41.732 --> 08:45.633
I was walking around,
and I'm wearing a hat, and I get nothing.

08:45.700 --> 08:48.067
-LEON: It's a hard business.
-You were more interesting to watch

08:48.167 --> 08:54.433
walk across the stage than Jonathan was,
and therein lies why you didn't fool us.

08:54.500 --> 08:57.800
Okay, so you're saying because Romy
was kind of heading over there

08:57.867 --> 09:00.333
while other stuff was going on elsewhere,
you were keeping an eye on her,

09:00.400 --> 09:03.133
that they didn't fool you,
that the trick was in some way dependent

09:03.200 --> 09:04.867
-on what Romy was doing?
-Yes.

09:04.933 --> 09:09.700
Okay, would that be the correct solution
to what happened?

09:10.300 --> 09:11.800
-That is not correct.
-Not correct.

09:11.867 --> 09:13.233
-(AUDIENCE GASPS)
-Okay.

09:13.300 --> 09:15.767
This is the way
you could have done the trick.

09:16.267 --> 09:19.200
When he picked the card,
which the card was a real selection.

09:19.267 --> 09:21.767
You did not force the card
out of the real decks.

09:21.833 --> 09:23.400
-That was all real, you could have...
-Right.

09:23.467 --> 09:26.667
...and we watched you
control that to the top,

09:26.733 --> 09:30.067
you could have handed her
the card with the box,

09:30.233 --> 09:32.900
she could've walked across the stage,
left it over there,

09:32.967 --> 09:35.567
it could have been copped over there,
walked across,

09:35.633 --> 09:37.433
-put on to the bottom of the skateboard...
-LEON: Absolutely.

09:37.500 --> 09:38.833
...then he could've brought it out
and done that.

09:38.900 --> 09:39.900
-Yes.
-Yes, it would have.

09:39.967 --> 09:41.000
PENN: But you didn't do it that way?

09:41.067 --> 09:42.067
-We did not do that.
-No.

09:42.133 --> 09:43.567
Okay, then you fooled us.

09:43.633 --> 09:45.733
-Yes!
-ROSS: Come on.

09:45.833 --> 09:47.633
-(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)
-(ROSS LAUGHS)

09:47.700 --> 09:49.067
That was the most awkward...

09:49.133 --> 09:50.533
So I jumped the gun.
That was so exciting.

09:50.667 --> 09:51.700
Thank you.

09:51.767 --> 09:53.500
LEON: Wow.
ROMY: Oh, my God.

09:53.567 --> 09:55.667
-Oh!
-Oh, my God, thank you so much.

09:55.733 --> 09:58.333
-Thank you.
-Thank you so much.

09:58.400 --> 09:59.433
Thank you, thank you.

10:00.733 --> 10:02.267
-Las Vegas, baby!
-Whoo!

10:02.333 --> 10:04.067
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

10:04.667 --> 10:06.067
(LEON LAUGHS)

10:06.133 --> 10:08.233
Ladies and gentlemen,
they fooled Penn and Teller.

10:08.300 --> 10:10.567
Romy and Leon, Leon and Romy,
congratulations,

10:10.633 --> 10:12.067
you're coming back to Vegas
as part of the show.

10:12.133 --> 10:13.333
-Let's hear it again.
-Yes!

10:13.400 --> 10:15.067
What a day! Congratulations.

10:15.133 --> 10:17.167
-Thank you so much.
-Romy and Leon, ladies and gentlemen.

10:17.233 --> 10:18.667
Leon and Romy.

10:22.067 --> 10:24.700
So far tonight, one magician
has fooled Penn and Teller

10:24.767 --> 10:26.400
and earned a trip back here to Vegas.

10:26.467 --> 10:29.600
So let's meet our next contender
and see if they're up to the task.

10:33.267 --> 10:34.600
<i>Hi, I am Mike Hammer,</i>

10:34.667 --> 10:37.600
<i>and I do a comedy magic show</i>
<i>here in Las Vegas five days a week.</i>

10:37.667 --> 10:39.433
I've been doing magic
ever since I was a kid.

10:39.500 --> 10:42.667
I thought it was cool back then,
and now it's... Eh, it's okay.

10:42.733 --> 10:44.067
Have you ever seen this one?

10:44.133 --> 10:45.700
<i>I will tell you, though,</i>
<i>the cool thing about magic</i>

10:45.767 --> 10:47.100
is it really does get you the chicks.

10:47.433 --> 10:48.700
How about...

10:49.233 --> 10:50.500
Chicks love the magic.

10:50.833 --> 10:52.700
They usually come out the other end.
You want to see that?

10:52.767 --> 10:54.433
-(RECORD SCRATCHING)
-I'm just saying. They're cards.

10:57.400 --> 10:58.500
I still got it.

10:58.567 --> 11:00.367
<i>Penn and Teller</i>
<i>are the best in the business.</i>

11:00.433 --> 11:02.600
<i>The one reason</i>
<i>I think I can fool Penn and Teller</i>

11:02.733 --> 11:05.267
is this is Vegas, and I'm gambling

11:05.333 --> 11:07.600
<i>that they've been too busy</i>
<i>to focus on the latest methods.</i>

11:08.200 --> 11:09.467
We'll see.

11:09.967 --> 11:11.300
(APPLAUSE)

11:13.200 --> 11:15.267
So, time to have some fun.

11:15.567 --> 11:18.333
This next performer
doesn't take his magic seriously

11:18.400 --> 11:21.233
or his career seriously
since he's a magician in the first place.

11:21.300 --> 11:23.767
-(LAUGHTER)
-Will you please welcome Mike Hammer?

11:23.833 --> 11:25.733
-(APPLAUSE)
-All right!

11:25.800 --> 11:27.167
Thank you.

11:28.667 --> 11:31.033
Thank you so much.
That was well-rehearsed applause.

11:31.600 --> 11:36.233
Tonight, what I'm about to show you is
brand-new unless you've seen me before.

11:36.300 --> 11:37.933
We do need someone from the audience.

11:38.000 --> 11:40.933
Don't look the other way
like I can't see you, sir.

11:41.000 --> 11:42.567
-You, what's your name?
-Kyle.

11:42.633 --> 11:44.633
Kyle, come up.
Give it up for Kyle, everybody.

11:44.700 --> 11:46.433
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

11:46.500 --> 11:49.867
How you doing, sir?
Look at you. You look like a professional.

11:49.933 --> 11:51.700
-Oh, yeah.
-Just don't screw it up, all right?

11:51.767 --> 11:53.467
Stand over here. This is Kyle, everybody.

11:53.533 --> 11:56.333
Listen, Kyle, have you ever been
on a blind date before?

11:56.400 --> 11:57.900
-No.
-No. You're not on one now?

11:57.967 --> 11:59.567
Okay, all right, all right.

11:59.733 --> 12:02.133
Look, I'm going
on a blind date, and actually,

12:02.200 --> 12:04.767
this is what she's supposed
to look like right over here.

12:04.833 --> 12:07.667
She told me that's what she looks like,
so we'll see what happens.

12:07.733 --> 12:09.333
Now, it's not important
what a woman looks like.

12:09.400 --> 12:12.067
What's important, Kyle,
is the way they're dressed.

12:12.167 --> 12:14.200
And that's where you come in.
Do you know women's clothing?

12:14.267 --> 12:15.633
-Not really.
-Not really.

12:15.700 --> 12:18.033
Well, I've got over here
some markers, all right?

12:18.100 --> 12:20.567
And I want you to just go ahead
and choose five markers.

12:20.833 --> 12:22.033
-All right.
-Five markers.

12:22.100 --> 12:25.467
Different-colored makers would be good.
There you go. Two... Oh, you're quick.

12:25.733 --> 12:27.700
-What do you do for a living there, Kyle?
-Landscaping.

12:27.767 --> 12:29.533
Landscaping. Wow. That's fun.

12:30.133 --> 12:32.333
So go ahead. Go ahead.

12:32.833 --> 12:34.233
There you go, that's probably...

12:34.300 --> 12:35.933
Yeah, okay, there you go.
Okay, good, good, good.

12:36.000 --> 12:37.167
We're just going to place them over here.

